# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-cost-explorer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Often considered a subset or quantitative tool of managerial accounting, its end goal is to advise the management on how to optimize business practices and processes based on cost efficiency and capability.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Cost accounting provides the detailed cost information that management needs to control current operations and plan for the future.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Cost accounting information is also commonly used in financial accounting, but its primary function is for use by managers to facilitate their decision-making.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] All types of businesses, whether manufacturing, trading or producing services, require cost accounting to track their activities.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Cost accounting has long been used to help managers understand the costs of running a business.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Modern cost accounting originated during the Industrial Revolution when the complexities of running large scale businesses led to the development of systems for recording and tracking costs to help business owners and managers make decisions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Various techniques used by cost accountants include standard costing and variance analysis, marginal costing and cost volume profit analysis, budgetary control, uniform costing, inter firm comparison, etc.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Evaluation of cost accounting is mainly due to the limitations of financial accounting.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Moreover, maintenance of cost records has been made compulsory in selected industries as notified by the government from time to time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] In the early industrial age most of the costs incurred by a business were what modern accountants call "variable costs" because they varied directly with the amount of production.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Money was spent on labour, raw materials, the power to run a factory, etc., in direct proportion to production.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Managers could simply total the variable costs for a product and use this as a rough guide for decision-making processes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Some costs tend to remain the same even during idle periods, unlike variable costs, which rise and fall with volume of work (and thus variable costs are higher in busy periods, and fall during idle periods).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Over time, these "fixed costs" have become more important to managers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Examples of fixed costs include the depreciation of plant and equipment, and the cost of departments such as maintenance, tooling, production control, purchasing, quality control, storage and handling, plant supervision and engineering.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] In the early nineteenth century, these costs were of little importance to most businesses.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] However, with the growth of railroads, steel and large scale manufacturing, by the late nineteenth century these costs were often more important than the variable cost of a product, and allocating them to a broad range of products led to bad decision making.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Managers must understand fixed costs in order to make decisions about products and pricing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example: a company produces railway coaches and has only one product.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] To make each coach, the company needs to purchase $60 of raw materials and components and pay 6 labourers $40 each.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Therefore, the total variable cost for each coach was $300.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Knowing that making a coach requires spending $300, managers know they cannot sell below that price without losing money on each coach.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Any price above $300 would make a contribution to the fixed costs of the company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] If the fixed costs are, say, $1000 per month for rent, insurance and owner's salary, the company could therefore sell 5 coaches per month for a total of $3000 (priced at $600 each), or 10 coaches for a total of $4500 (priced at $450 each), and make a profit of $500 in each case.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The materials directly contributed to a product and those easily identifiable in the finished product are called **direct materials**.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, paper in books, wood in furniture, plastic in a water tank, and leather in shoes are direct materials.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Other, usually lower cost items or supporting material used in the production of in a finished product are called **indirect materials**.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, lubricants used to keep machines running, or the chemicals used during the garment manufacturing processes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Furthermore, these can be categorized into three different types of inventories that must be accounted for in different ways; raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Any wages paid to workers or a group of workers which may directly co-relate to any specific activity of production, maintenance, transportation of material, or product, and directly associate in the conversion of raw material into finished goods are called **direct labour**.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Wages paid to trainees or apprentices does not come under the category of direct labour as they have no significant value.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] These categories are flexible, sometimes overlapping as different cost accounting principles are applied.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By function: production, administration, selling and distribution, or research and development.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By behavior: fixed, variable, or semi-variable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Fixed costs remain unchanged irrespective of changes in the production volume over a given period of time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Variable costs change according to the volume of production.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Semi-variable costs are partly fixed and partly variable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By controllability: Controllable costs are those which can be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Uncontrollable costs cannot be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By normality: normal costs and abnormal costs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Normal costs arise during routine day-to-day business operations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Abnormal costs arise because of any abnormal activity or event not part of routine business operations, such as accidents or natural disasters.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By time: Historical costs and predetermined costs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Historical costs are costs incurred in the past.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Predetermined costs are computed in advance on basis of factors affecting cost elements.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Differential costs: This cost is the difference in total cost resulting from selecting one alternative over another.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Opportunity costs: The value of a benefit sacrificed in favour of an alternative course of action.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Relevant cost: The relevant cost is a cost which is relevant in various decisions of management.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Replacement cost: This cost is the cost at which existing items of material or fixed assets can be replaced at present or at a future date.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Shutdown cost: Costs incurred if operations are shut down, and which would not occur if operations are continued.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Capacity cost: The cost incurred by a company for providing production, administration and selling and distribution capabilities in order to perform various functions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Sunk cost: A cost already incurred, which cannot be recovered.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Standard Costing is a technique of Cost Accounting to compare the actual costs with standard costs (that are pre-defined) with the help of Variance Analysis.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] It is used to understand the variations of product costs in manufacturing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Standard costing allocates fixed costs incurred in an accounting period to the goods produced during that period.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] It also essentially enabled managers to ignore the fixed costs, and look at the results of each period in relation to the "standard cost" for any given product.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For Example: if the railway coach company normally produced 40 coaches per month, and the fixed costs were still $1000/month, then each coach could be said to incur an Operating Cost/overhead of $25 =($1000 / 40).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Adding this to the variable costs of $300 per coach produced a full cost of $325 per coach.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] This method tended to slightly distort the resulting unit cost, but in mass-production industries that made one product line, and where the fixed costs were relatively low, the distortion was very minor.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For Example: if the railway coach company made 100 coaches one month, then the unit cost would become $310 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 100)).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] If the next month the company made 50 coaches, then the unit cost = $320 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 50)), a relatively minor difference.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] As business became more complex and began producing a greater variety of products, the use of cost accounting to make decisions to maximize profitability came into question.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Management circles became increasingly aware of the theory of constraints in the 1980s and began to understand that "every production process has a limiting factor" somewhere in the chain of production.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] As business management learned to identify the constraints, they increasingly adopted throughput accounting to manage them and "maximize the *throughput dollars*" (or other currency) from each unit of constrained resource.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Throughput accounting aims to make the best use of scarce resources (bottleneck) in a JIT (Just in time) environment.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] "Throughput", in this context, refers to the amount of money obtained from sales minus the cost of materials that have gone into making them.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Activity-based costing (ABC) is a system for assigning costs to products based on the activities they require.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] In this case, activities are those regular actions performed inside a company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] "Talking with the customer regarding invoice questions" is an example of activity inside most companies.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Companies may be moved to adopt ABC by a need to improve costing accuracy, that is, understand better the true costs and profitability of individual products, services, or initiatives.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] ABC gets closer to true costs in these areas by turning many costs that standard cost accounting views as indirect costs essentially into direct costs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] By contrast, standard cost accounting typically determines so-called indirect and overhead costs simply as a percentage of certain direct costs, which may or may not reflect actual resource usage for individual items.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Under ABC, accountants assign 100% of each employee's time to the different activities performed inside a company (many will use surveys to have the workers themselves assign their time to the different activities).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The accountant then can determine the total cost spent on each activity by summing up the percentage of each worker's salary spent on that activity.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] A company can use the resulting activity cost data to determine where to focus its operational improvements.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, a job-based manufacturer may find that a high percentage of its workers are spending their time trying to figure out a hastily written customer order.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Via (ABC) Activity-based costing, the accountants now have a currency amount pegged to the activity of "Researching Customer Work Order Specifications".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Senior management can now decide how much focus or money to budget for resolving this process deficiency.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Activity-based management includes (but is not restricted to) the use of activity-based costing to manage a business.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] While (ABC) Activity-based costing may be able to pinpoint the cost of each activity and resources into the ultimate product, the process could be tedious, costly and subject to errors.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] As it is a tool for a more accurate way of allocating fixed costs into a product, these fixed costs do not vary according to each month's production volume.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, the elimination of one product would not eliminate the overhead or even direct labour cost assigned to it.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Activity-based costing (ABC) better identifies product costing in the long run, but may not be too helpful in day-to-day decision-making.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Recently, Mocciaro Li Destri, Picone and Minà (2012) proposed a performance and cost measurement system that integrates the Economic Value Added criteria with Process-Based Costing (PBC).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The EVA-PBC methodology allows us to implement the EVA management logic not only at the firm level, but also at lower levels of the organization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] EVA-PBC methodology plays an interesting role in bringing strategy back into financial performance measures.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Lean accounting has developed in recent years to provide the accounting, control, and measurement methods supporting lean manufacturing and other applications of lean thinking such as healthcare, construction, insurance, banking, education, government and other industries.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] There are two main thrusts for Lean Accounting.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The first is the application of lean methods to the company's accounting, control, and measurement processes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] This is not different from applying lean methods to any other processes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The objective is to eliminate waste, free up capacity, speed up the process, eliminate errors & defects, and make the process clear and understandable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Lean Accounting does not require the traditional management accounting methods like standard costing, activity-based costing, variance reporting, cost-plus pricing, complex transactional control systems, and untimely and confusing financial reports.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The cost-volume-profit analysis is the systematic examination of the relationship between selling prices, sales, production volumes, costs, expenses and profits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] This analysis provides very useful information for decision-making in the management of a company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, the analysis can be used in establishing sales prices, in the product mix selection to sell, in the decision to choose marketing strategies, and in the analysis of the impact on profits by changes in costs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] In the current environment of business, a business administration must act and take decisions in a fast and accurate manner.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] As a result, the importance of cost-volume-profit is still increasing as time passes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] A relationship between the cost, volume and profit is the contribution margin.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The contribution margin is the revenue excess from sales over variable costs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The concept of contribution margin is particularly useful in the planning of business because it gives an insight into the potential profits that a business can generate.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The contribution margin can also be expressed as a percentage.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The contribution margin ratio, which is sometimes called the profit-volume ratio, indicates the percentage of each sales dollar available to cover fixed costs and to provide operating revenue.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The contribution margin ratio measures the effect on operating income of an increase or a decrease in sales volume.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] For example, assume that the management of Fusion, Inc. is studying the effect of adding $80,000 in sales orders.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Multiplying the contribution margin ratio (40%) by the change in sales volume ($80,000) indicates that operating income will increase $32,000 if additional orders are obtained.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Variable costs as a percentage of sales are equal to 100% minus the contribution margin ratio.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] The total contribution margin $432,000, can also be computed directly by multiplying the sales by the contribution margin ratio ($1,080,000 X 40%).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Relevant cost data or pricing data may be required from the supplier, in order to undertake a "cost realism analysis", also known as a "price realism analysis".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/cost-management] Similarly, where a government agency requests a fixed price submission, provision may be made for a cost or price realism analysis to take place during the evaluation process.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Payment terms are usually stated on the invoice.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] These may specify that the buyer has a maximum number of days to pay and is sometimes offered a discount if paid before the due date.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The buyer could have already paid for the products or services listed on the invoice.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] To avoid confusion and consequent unnecessary communications from buyer to seller, some sellers clearly state in large and capital letters on an invoice whether it has already been paid.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] From a seller's point of view, an invoice is a *sales invoice*.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] From a buyer's point of view, an invoice is a *purchase invoice*.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The document indicates the buyer and seller, but the term *invoice* indicates money is owed *or* owing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Invoices appear as one of the very earliest manifestations of written records in ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The practice of invoicing can be traced back to ancient civilizations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Around 5,000 years ago, merchants in Mesopotamia used cuneiform script on clay tablets to document trade transactions, including details such as quantities, prices, and the parties involved.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] These records functioned as contracts and receipts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] In ancient Egypt, transactions and tax records were documented on papyrus scrolls, serving as an early method of financial record-keeping.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The invention of paper in China around AD 105 facilitated advancements in documentation, eventually spreading to the Middle East and Europe.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] During the Middle Ages, European merchants began using handwritten invoices to detail sales transactions, often recording information such as dates, descriptions of goods, quantities and prices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The printing press was introduced in the 15th century that enabled the production of standardized invoice forms, contributing to more consistent financial documentation.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] By the 19th century, printed invoices became widespread, with businesses incorporating elements such as company names, addresses, and logos.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The 20th and 21st centuries saw the transition to digital and automated invoicing systems, further improving efficiency and record-keeping practices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The typical format of an invoice starts with a header prominently featuring the term "Invoice".
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] This is usually followed by information needed to establish the context of the transactions such as the name, address, and contact information of the parties involved (e.g. buyer and seller) and important dates such as when payment must be received.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The main body of the invoice provides an itemized list of goods or services rendered, specifying descriptions, unit prices, quantities, and total prices for each line item.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Additional financial elements like taxes, shipping charges, and discounts are separately enumerated and added to the subtotal to calculate the grand total amount due.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The invoice often concludes with standardized elements or other information not included in the pre-body.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] This structured format serves various functions, including billing, accounting, auditing, and, in cases of disagreement, legal evidence for dispute resolution.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] In countries where wire transfer is the preferred method of settling debts, the printed bill will contain the bank account number of the creditor and usually a reference code to be passed along with the transaction identifying the payer.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The European Union requires a VAT (value-added tax) identification number for official VAT invoices, which all VAT-registered businesses are required to issue to their customers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] In the UK, this number may be omitted on invoices if the words "this is not a VAT invoice" are present on the invoice.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Such an invoice is called a pro-forma invoice, and is not an adequate substitute for a full VAT invoice for VAT-registered customers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] In Canada, the registration number for GST purposes must be furnished for all supplies over $30 made by a registered supplier in order to claim input tax credits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Recommendations about invoices used in international trade are also provided by the UNECE Committee on Trade, which involves a more detailed description of the logistics aspect of merchandise and, therefore may be convenient for international logistics and customs procedures.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Some invoices are no longer paper-based, but rather transmitted electronically over the Internet.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] It is still common for electronic remittance or invoicing to be printed in order to maintain paper records.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Standards for electronic invoicing vary widely from country to country.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) standards such as the United Nations' EDIFACT standard include message encoding guidelines for electronic invoices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The EDIFACT is followed up in the UN/CEFACT ebXML syntax cross industry invoice.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The United Nations standard for electronic invoices ("INVOIC") includes standard codes for transmitting header information (common to the entire invoice) and codes for transmitting details for each of the line items (products or services).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The "INVOIC" standard can also be used to transmit credit and debit memos.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] In the European Union legislation was passed in 2010 in the form of directive 2010/45/EU to facilitate the growth of Electronic Invoicing across all its member states.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] This legislation caters for varying VAT and inter-country invoicing requirements within the EU, in addition to legislating for the authenticity and integrity of invoices being sent electronically.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] It is estimated that in 2011 alone roughly 5 million EU businesses will have sent Electronic Invoices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The XML message format for electronic invoices has been used since the inception of XML in 1998.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Open Application Group Integration Specification (OAGIS) has included an invoice since 2001.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The Open Applications Group (OAGi) has a working relationship with UN/CEFACT where OAGi and its members participate in defining many of the Technology and Methodology specifications.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] OAGi also includes support for these Technology and Methodology specifications within OAGIS.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] There are two XML-based standards currently being developed.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] One is the cross industry invoice under development by the United Nations standards body UN/CEFACT and the other is Universal Business Language (UBL) which is issued by Organization for the Advancement of Structured Information Standards (OASIS).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Implementations of invoices based on UBL are common, most importantly in the public sector in Denmark as it was the first country where the use of UBL was mandated by law for all invoices in the public sector.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Further implementations are underway in the Scandinavian countries as result of the North European Subset project.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Implementations are also underway in Italy, Spain, and the Netherlands (UBL 2.0) and with the European Commission itself.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] The NES work has been transferred to European Committee for Standardization (CEN), the standards body of the European Union), workshop CEN/BII, for public procurement in Europe.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] There UBL procurement documents are implemented between various European countries.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] An agreement was made between UBL and UN/CEFACT for convergence of the two XML messages standards with the objective of merging the two standards into one before end of 2009, including the provision of an upgrade path for implementations started in either standard.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] It’s a global network that allows businesses and governments to exchange invoices securely.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Just direct system-to-system communication.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Imagine sending money through a banking network—that’s PEPPOL, but for invoices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] ISDOC is a standard that was developed in the Czech Republic as a universal format for electronic invoices.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] On 16 October 2008, 14 companies and the Czech government signed a declaration to use this format within one year in their products.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] After implantation of the Goods and Services Tax (GST) in India, concept of e-invoicing has been introduced for businesses with a turnover of more than Rs 5 crore from 1 August 2023.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Now reporting of business-to-business (B2B) invoices for notified category of taxpayer.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Organizations purchasing goods and services usually have a process in place for approving payment of invoices based on an employee's confirmation that the goods or services have been received.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Typically, when paying an invoice, a remittance advice will be sent to the supplier to inform them their invoice has been paid.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] Non-payment and late payment of invoices is estimated to be the cause of 25% of corporate bankruptcies.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/invoice] To mitigate this, the European Commission has introduced the Late Payment Directive that sets a limit on businesses to settle their invoices within 60 days.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In business, predictive models exploit patterns found in historical and transactional data to identify risks and opportunities.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Models capture relationships among many factors to allow assessment of risk or potential associated with a particular set of conditions, guiding decision-making for candidate transactions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Since 2022, the field has evolved significantly with the integration of generative AI and large language models (LLMs), moving from purely numerical forecasting to "Predictive GenAI," which combines forecasting with automated content generation and agentic workflows.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics is a set of business intelligence (BI) technologies that uncovers relationships and patterns within large volumes of data that can be used to predict behavior and events.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Unlike other BI technologies, predictive analytics is forward-looking, using past events to anticipate the future.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics statistical techniques include data modeling, machine learning, artificial intelligence, deep learning algorithms and data mining.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Often the unknown event of interest is in the future, but predictive analytics can be applied to any type of unknown whether it be in the past, present or future.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] For example, identifying suspects after a crime has been committed, or credit card fraud as it occurs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The core of predictive analytics relies on capturing relationships between explanatory variables and the predicted variables from past occurrences, and exploiting them to predict the unknown outcome.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The accuracy and usability of results depend greatly on the level of data analysis and the quality of assumptions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Traditionally, predictive analytics focused on discriminative models—algorithms that classify data or predict a value (e.g., "Will this customer churn?").
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Since 2023, the emergence of Generative AI has expanded the field's capabilities.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The modern technology stack for predictive analytics, often referred to as the "Modern Data Stack," has shifted from on-premise servers to cloud-native, real-time architectures.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The approaches and techniques used to conduct predictive analytics can broadly be grouped into regression techniques and machine learning techniques.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Machine learning can be defined as the ability of a machine to learn and then mimic human behavior that requires intelligence.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] This is accomplished through artificial intelligence, algorithms, and models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] ARIMA models are a common example of time series models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] These models use autoregression, which means the model can be fitted with a regression software that will use machine learning to do most of the regression analysis and smoothing.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] ARIMA models are known to have no overall trend, but instead have a variation around the average that has a constant amplitude, resulting in statistically similar time patterns.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Through this, variables are analyzed and data is filtered in order to better understand and predict future values.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] One example of an ARIMA method is exponential smoothing models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Exponential smoothing takes into account the difference in importance between older and newer data sets, as the more recent data is more accurate and valuable in predicting future values.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In order to accomplish this, exponents are utilized to give newer data sets a larger weight in the calculations than the older sets.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Time series models are a subset of machine learning that utilize time series in order to understand and forecast data using past values.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] A time series is the sequence of a variable's value over equally spaced periods, such as years or quarters in business applications.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] To accomplish this, the data must be smoothed, or the random variance of the data must be removed in order to reveal trends in the data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] There are multiple ways to accomplish this.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Single moving average methods utilize smaller and smaller numbered sets of past data to decrease error that is associated with taking a single average, making it a more accurate average than it would be to take the average of the entire data set.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Centered moving average methods utilize the data found in the single moving average methods by taking an average of the median-numbered data set.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] However, as the median-numbered data set is difficult to calculate with even-numbered data sets, this method works better with odd-numbered data sets than even.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive modeling is a statistical technique used to predict future behavior.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] It utilizes predictive models to analyze a relationship between a specific unit in a given sample and one or more features of the unit.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The objective of these models is to assess the possibility that a unit in another sample will display the same pattern.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive model solutions can be considered a type of data mining technology.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The models can analyze both historical and current data and generate a model in order to predict potential future outcomes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Regardless of the methodology used, in general, the process of creating predictive models involves the same steps.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] First, it is necessary to determine the project objectives and desired outcomes and translate these into predictive analytic objectives and tasks.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Then, analyze the source data to determine the most appropriate data and model building approach (models are only as useful as the applicable data used to build them).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Select and transform the data in order to create models.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Create and test models in order to evaluate if they are valid and will be able to meet project goals and metrics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Apply the model's results to appropriate business processes (identifying patterns in the data doesn't necessarily mean a business will understand how to take advantage or capitalize on it).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Afterward, manage and maintain models in order to standardize and improve performance (demand will increase for model management in order to meet new compliance regulations).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Generally, regression analysis uses structural data along with the past values of independent variables and the relationship between them and the dependent variable to form predictions.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In linear regression, a plot is constructed with the previous values of the dependent variable plotted on the Y-axis and the independent variable that is being analyzed plotted on the X-axis.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] A regression line is then constructed by a statistical program representing the relationship between the independent and dependent variables which can be used to predict values of the dependent variable based only on the independent variable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] With the regression line, the program also shows a slope intercept equation for the line which includes an addition for the error term of the regression, where the higher the value of the error term the less precise the regression model is.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In order to decrease the value of the error term, other independent variables are introduced to the model, and similar analyses are performed on these independent variables.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] An important aspect of auditing includes analytical review.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In analytical review, the reasonableness of reported account balances being investigated is determined.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The ARIMA method for analytical review uses time-series analysis on past audited balances in order to create the conditional expectations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] These conditional expectations are then compared to the actual balances reported on the audited account in order to determine how close the reported balances are to the expectations.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] If the reported balances are close to the expectations, the accounts are not audited further.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] If the reported balances are very different from the expectations, there is a higher possibility of a material accounting error and a further audit is conducted.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Regression analysis methods are deployed in a similar way, except the regression model used assumes the availability of only one independent variable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The materiality of the independent variable contributing to the audited account balances are determined using past account balances along with present structural data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Materiality is the importance of an independent variable in its relationship to the dependent variable.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In this case, the dependent variable is the account balance.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Through this the most important independent variable is used in order to create the conditional expectation and, similar to the ARIMA method, the conditional expectation is then compared to the account balance reported and a decision is made based on the closeness of the two balances.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The STAR methods operate using regression analysis, and fall into two methods.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The first is the STAR monthly balance approach, and the conditional expectations made and regression analysis used are both tied to one month being audited.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The other method is the STAR annual balance approach, which happens on a larger scale by basing the conditional expectations and regression analysis on one year being audited.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Besides the difference in the time being audited, both methods operate the same, by comparing expected and reported balances to determine which accounts to further investigate.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] As we move into a world of technological advances where more and more data is created and stored digitally, businesses are looking for ways to take advantage of this opportunity and use this information to help generate profits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics can be used and is capable of providing many benefits to a wide range of businesses, including asset management firms, insurance companies, communication companies, and many other firms.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] In a study conducted by IDC Analyze the Future, Dan Vasset and Henry D.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Morris explain how an asset management firm used predictive analytics to develop a better marketing campaign.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] They went from a mass marketing approach to a customer-centric approach, where instead of sending the same offer to each customer, they would personalize each offer based on their customer.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics was used to predict the likelihood that a possible customer would accept a personalized offer.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Due to the marketing campaign and predictive analytics, the firm's acceptance rate skyrocketed, with three times the number of people accepting their personalized offers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Technological advances in predictive analytics have increased its value to firms.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] One technological advancement is more powerful computers, and with this predictive analytics has become able to create forecasts on large data sets much faster.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] With the increased computing power also comes more data and applications, meaning a wider array of inputs to use with predictive analytics.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Another technological advance includes a more user-friendly interface, allowing a smaller barrier of entry and less extensive training required for employees to utilize the software and applications effectively.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Due to these advancements, many more corporations are adopting predictive analytics and seeing the benefits in employee efficiency and effectiveness, as well as profits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] ARIMA univariate and multivariate models can be used in forecasting a company's future cash flows, with its equations and calculations based on the past values of certain factors contributing to cash flows.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Using time-series analysis, the values of these factors can be analyzed and extrapolated to predict the future cash flows for a company.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] For the univariate models, past values of cash flows are the only factor used in the prediction.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Meanwhile the multivariate models use multiple factors related to accrual data, such as operating income before depreciation.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Another model used in predicting cash-flows was developed in 1998 and is known as the Dechow, Kothari, and Watts model, or DKW (1998).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] DKW (1998) uses regression analysis in order to determine the relationship between multiple variables and cash flows.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Through this method, the model found that cash-flow changes and accruals are negatively related, specifically through current earnings, and using this relationship predicts the cash flows for the next period.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The DKW (1998) model derives this relationship through the relationships of accruals and cash flows to accounts payable and receivable, along with inventory.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Some child welfare agencies have started using predictive analytics to flag high risk cases.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] For example, in Hillsborough County, Florida, the child welfare agency's use of a predictive modeling tool has prevented abuse-related child deaths in the target population.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] The predicting of the outcome of juridical decisions can be done by AI programs.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] These programs can be used as assistive tools for professions in this industry.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Often the focus of analysis is not the consumer but the product, portfolio, firm, industry or even the economy.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] For example, a retailer might be interested in predicting store-level demand for inventory management purposes.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Or the Federal Reserve Board might be interested in predicting the unemployment rate for the next year.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] These types of problems can be addressed by predictive analytics using time series techniques (see below).
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] They can also be addressed via machine learning approaches which transform the original time series into a feature vector space, where the learning algorithm finds patterns that have predictive power.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Many businesses have to account for risk exposure due to their different services and determine the costs needed to cover the risk.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics can help underwrite these quantities by predicting the chances of illness, default, bankruptcy, etc.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics can streamline the process of customer acquisition by predicting the future risk behavior of a customer using application level data.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics in the form of credit scores have reduced the amount of time it takes for loan approvals, especially in the mortgage market.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Proper predictive analytics can lead to proper pricing decisions, which can help mitigate future risk of default.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/predictive-analytics] Predictive analytics can be used to mitigate moral hazard and prevent accidents from occurring.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] For manufacturing, as TCO is typically compared with doing business overseas, it goes beyond the initial manufacturing cycle time and cost to make parts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO includes a variety of cost of doing business items, for example, ship and re-ship, and opportunity costs, while it also considers incentives developed for an alternative approach.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Incentives and other variables include tax credits, common language, expedited delivery, and customer-oriented supplier visits.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO, when incorporated into a financial benefit analysis, provides a cost basis for determining the total economic value of an investment.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include: return on investment, internal rate of return, economic value added, return on information technology, and rapid economic justification.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] The roots of this concept date at least back to the first quarter of the twentieth century.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Many different methodologies and software tools have been developed to analyze TCO in various operational contexts.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis includes total cost of acquisition and operating costs, as well as costs related to replacement or upgrades at the end of the life cycle.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis is used to gauge the viability of any capital investment.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] An enterprise may use it as a product/process comparison tool.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] It is also used by credit markets and financing agencies.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO directly relates to an enterprise's asset and/or related systems total costs across all projects and processes, thus giving a picture of the profitability over time.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO analysis was popularized by the Gartner Group in 1987.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO is applied to the analysis of information technology products, seeking to quantify the financial impact of deploying a product over its life cycle.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] These technologies include software and hardware, and training.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] In the case of comparing TCO of existing versus proposed solutions, consideration should be put toward costs required to maintain the existing solution that may not necessarily be required for a proposed solution.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include cost of manual processing that are only required to support lack of existing automation, and extended support personnel.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Total cost of ownership can be applied to the structure and systems of a single building or a campus of buildings.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Pioneered by Doug Christensen and the facilities department at Brigham Young University starting in the 1980s, the concept gained more traction in educational facilities in the early 21st century.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] A key objective of planning, constructing, operating, and managing buildings via TCO principals is for building owners and facility professionals to predict needs and deliver data-driven results.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO can be applied any time during the life of a facility asset to manage cost inputs for the life of the structure or system into the future.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA, an ANSI Accredited Standards Developer, published *APPA 1000-1 – Total Cost of Ownership for Facilities Asset Management (TCO) – Part 1: Key Principles* as an American National Standard in December 2017.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-1 provides financial officers, facility professionals, architects, planners, construction workforce, and operations and maintenance (O&M) personnel the foundation of a standardized and holistic approach to implementing TCO key principles.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Implementation of TCO key principles can improve decision making, maximizing financial strategies over the life of an asset, starting at the planning and design stage and extends to the end of the asset's life.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-2, slated for publication in 2019, will focus on implementation and application of key TCO principals in facility management.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] The TCO concept is easily applicable to the transportation industry and to motor vehicle ownership, for example, the TCO defines the cost of owning an automobile from the time of purchase by the owner, through its operation and maintenance to the time it leaves the possession of the owner.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Comparative TCO studies between various models help consumers choose a car to fit their needs and budget.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] For personal vehicles in the United States, AAA's annual *Your Driving Costs* study estimated the average total cost of new-vehicle ownership at $11,577 per year in 2025, driven by depreciation, financing, fuel, insurance, maintenance, and license fees.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] In the truck industry, TCO is an essential factor for truck fleet managers.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] By calculating the Total Cost of Ownership of a truck, the truck manager obtains a price per kilometer that varies according to fuel costs, the purchase price, and the resale price of the truck.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] If the truck is financed, the TCO also varies according to the interest rate on the loan.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] These factors in the trucking industry allow managers to make a clearer choice about which truck to select for their truck fleet, because when a transportation company wants to acquire 1 to 10 trucks, TCO is an essential factor to consider for the company's cash flow.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO does not assess how well a solution offers value for money, or how well it fits with an organisation's strategic objectives.
[src:aws-cost-explorer/total-cost-of-ownership] Some TCO analyses may include social and environmental costs but this is not always the case.
